An Act relative to protecting health insurance coverage.
Whereas, The deferred operation of this act would tend to defeat its purpose, which is to
address health insurance coverage in the commonwealth, therefore it is hereby declared to be an
emergency law, necessary for the immediate preservation of the public convenience.
Be it enacted by the Senate and House of Representatives in General Court assembled, and by the authority
of the same, as follows:
1 SECTION 1. Chapter 149 of the General Laws is hereby amended by inserting, after
2 section 188, the following section:-
3 Section 188A. (a) As used in this section, the following words shall, unless the context
4 clearly requires otherwise, have the following meanings:
5 “Authority”, the commonwealth health insurance connector authority established
6 pursuant to chapter 176Q.
7 “Contributing employer”, an employer that offers a group health plan, as defined in 26
8 U.S.C. 5000(b)(1), to which the employer makes a fair and reasonable premium contribution , as
9 defined in regulation by the authority.
1 of 6

10 “Department”, the department of unemployment assistance.
11 “Director”, the director of the department of unemployment assistance.
12 “Employee”, an individual employed by an employer subject to this chapter for at least 1
13 month; provided that, for the purpose of this section self-employed individuals shall not be
14 considered employees.
15 “Employer”, any employing unit, as defined in section 1 of chapter 151A, or any
16 employer, as defined in section 1 of chapter 152.
17 “Fair share employer contribution”, an employer’s per-employee contribution established
18 under paragraph (1) of subsection (b) paid at a time and in manner prescribed by the director.
19 (b)(1) To more equitably distribute the costs of health care provided to uninsured
20 residents of the commonwealth, each employer that: (i) employs 50 or more full-time equivalent
21 employees in the commonwealth and (ii) is not a contributing employer may be required to pay a
22 per-employee contribution at a time and in a manner prescribed by the director.
23 (2) The fair share employer contribution shall be pro-rated by a fraction that shall not
24 exceed 1, the numerator of which is the number of hours worked in the quarter by all of the
25 employer's employees and the denominator of which is the product of the number of employees
26 employed by an employer during that quarter multiplied by 500 hours.
27 (c) The executive director of the authority shall, in consultation with the director,
28 annually determine the fair share employer contribution rate based on the best available data and
29 under the following provisions:
2 of 6

30 (1) The per-user share of private sector liability shall be calculated annually by
31 dividing the sum of hospital liability and third-party payor liability for uncompensated care, as
32 defined by law, by the total number of individuals in the most recently completed fiscal year
33 whose care was reimbursed in whole or in part by the health safety net office.
34 (2) The total number of employees in the most recent fiscal year on whose behalf
35 health care services were reimbursed in whole or in part by the health safety net office, shall be
36 calculated. In calculating this number, the authority shall use all resources available to enable it
37 to determine the employment status of individuals for whom reimbursements were made,
38 including quarterly wage reports maintained by the department of revenue.
39 (3) The total number of employees as calculated in paragraph (2) shall be adjusted
40 by multiplying that number by the per centage of employers in the commonwealth that are not
41 contributing employers, as determined by the authority.
42 (4) The total cost of liability associated with employees of non-contributing
43 employers shall be determined by multiplying the number of employees, as calculated in
44 paragraph (3) by the per-user share of private sector liability as calculated in paragraph (1).
45 (5) The fair share employer contribution shall be calculated by dividing the total
46 cost of liability as calculated in paragraph (4) by the total number of employees of employers
47 that are not contributing employers, as determined by the authority.
48 (6) The fair share employer contribution, as determined in paragraph (5) shall be
49 adjusted annually to reflect medical inflation, using an appropriate index as determined by the
50 authority.
3 of 6

51 (7) The total dollar amount of health care services provided by physicians to non-
52 elderly, uninsured residents of the commonwealth for which no reimbursement is made from the
53 Health Safety Net Trust Fund, established in section 66 of chapter 118E, shall be calculated
54 using a survey of physicians or other data source that the authority determines is most accurate.
55 (8) The per-employee cost of uncompensated physician care shall be calculated
56 by dividing the dollar amount of such services, as calculated in paragraph (7) by the total number
57 of employees of contributing employers in the commonwealth, as estimated by the authority
58 using the most accurate data source available, as determined by the authority.
59 (9) The annual fair share employer contribution shall be calculated by adding the
60 fair share employer contribution as calculated in paragraph (6) and the per-employee cost of
61 unreimbursed physician care, as calculated in paragraph (8).
62 (10) Notwithstanding this section, the total annual fair share employer
63 contribution shall not exceed $295 per employee, which may be made in a single payment or in
64 equal amounts semi-annually or quarterly, at the employer's discretion.
65 (11) In calculating the fair share employer contribution, employees who have qualifying
66 health insurance coverage from a spouse, parent, veteran's plan, Medicare or a plan or plans due
67 to disability or retirement shall not be included in the numerator or denominator for purposes of
68 determining whether an employer is a contributing employer. The employer shall keep and
69 maintain proof of their employee's insurance status, in a reasonable manner as defined by the
70 authority.
71 (d)(1) The director shall assess each employer liable for a fair share employer
72 contribution in a quarter an amount based on 25 per cent of the annual fair share employer
